On sunny days, the birds were high in the air at the limit of visibility, and on rainy days they descended to a height of 60â€“150 m above the ground. Rathbun connected the flight altitude with the level of atmospheric pressure: at low pressure, birds fly closer to the ground, and at high pressure, they rise to the border visibility and above, are poorly distinguishable even with binoculars [8]. The black american swift in flight
 In July and August, black american swifts followed the same routes, however, separate groups were smaller, and isolated pairs were sometimes found. At the same time, in the evening, birds usually returned very quickly along the shortest route. with the departure of chicks from nests.